Government institutions including national game reserves, roads, dispensaries and hospitals, cattle dips, schools, electricity lines, colleges, and parks have been submerged, forcing the state to spend millions of shillings on repair. For example, the Lake Nakuru National Park has spent Sh50 million to rehabilitate the park infrastructure and another Sh105 million to rehabilitate the 20 kilometre road damaged by the rising water levels. 

The Marigat-Chemolingot Road has also been cut off by flood waters at Loruk and villagers have to use boats to cross over, even with the risk of being attacked by crocodiles. 

Schools affected include Salabani secondary, Ng’ambo Girls, Lake Bogoria Girls’, Ngambo , Sintaan,Kokwo, Leswa, Lorok,Loruk,Loropil, Noosukro, Kiserian, Sokotei and Salabani primary schools. 






Flamingos at Lake Bogoria Game Reserve in Baringo County.The birds are dying in hundreds daily as they are trapped by thorny Mathenge plant. 
Photo credit: Cheboite Kigen

 

In Lake Naivasha, over 20km road network estimated at Sh100 million and power transformers are submerged exposing the community to great risk. 



